From Axiom to R
The claim here is in a sense weaker, but still interesting. It says that if the R in \(\langle W, R \rangle\) is not transitive, then there is some way to make \(\Box A \rightarrow \Box \Box A\) false. That is, if you pick the right values for the following three things:

The point \(w\) in \(W\);
The substitution instance for \(A\)
The valuation function \(V\);

then \(\Box A \rightarrow \Box \Box A\) will be false.

